18. Prepositions have some colloquial or archaic uses :

a) By an extension of the idea of source a, ab is used of possession : Mil. Glor. 160, quemque a milite, “ any one of the soldier’s people ”; Ps. 735, a me dare, “ to give from my property.” Cf. Ter. Ad. 940, de te largitor = the common de tuo.

b) cum with abl. is loosely used for the dat„ the acc„ or an adj.: Pers. 109, mentionem facere cum aliqu03 Ps. 909, cauere; Bacch. 1056, pignus dare, etc.; capt. 203, curn catenis sumus, “chained ”i Ps. 158, te cum securi: qui securim habes.
